{"parse":{"title":"Who Killed Homer?","pageid":58413347,"revid":858385744,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><i><b>Who Killed Homer?</b>: The Demise of Classical Education and the Recovery of Greek Wisdom,</i> is a 1988 book by <a href=\"/wiki/Classics\" title=\"Classics\">Classics</a> scholars <a href=\"/wiki/Victor_Davis_Hanson\" title=\"Victor Davis Hanson\">Victor Davis Hanson</a> and John Heath.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-KnoxReview_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-KnoxReview-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Reviewing <i>Who Killed Homer?</i> for <a href=\"/wiki/Foreign_Affairs\" title=\"Foreign Affairs\">Foreign Affairs</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Francis_Fukuyama\" title=\"Francis Fukuyama\">Francis Fukuyama</a> described it as \"ostensibly\" focused on the decline of classical studies, but \"really about the loss of a common, humanistic core in contemporary education and culture.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-FukuyamaReview_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-FukuyamaReview-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Controversy\">Controversy</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Who_Killed_Homer%3F&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Controversy\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p><i>Who Killed Homer?,</i> was a polemic book criticizing classics scholars including <a href=\"/wiki/Nancy_Sorkin_Rabinowitz\" title=\"Nancy Sorkin Rabinowitz\">Nancy Sorkin Rabinowitz</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Judith_Hallett\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Judith Hallett\">Judith Hallett</a>, and <a href=\"/wiki/Amy_Richlin\" title=\"Amy Richlin\">Amy Richlin</a>, who, in the authors' opinion, misinterpreted and debased classical texts in the service of <a href=\"/wiki/Critical_theory\" title=\"Critical theory\">critical theory</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Feminism\" title=\"Feminism\">feminism</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Identity_politics\" title=\"Identity politics\">identity politics</a> and other political causes.<sup id=\"cite_ref-KottaTradition_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-KottaTradition-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-LewisUpdate_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-LewisUpdate-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Who_Killed_Homer%3F&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Doty, Ralph E. \u201cThe Classical Outlook.\u201d The Classical Outlook, vol. 76, no. 1, 1998, pp. 35\u201335. JSTOR, JSTOR, www.jstor.org/stable/43938160.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-KnoxReview-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-KnoxReview_2-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\">Knox, Bernard (5 April 1998). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://search.proquest.com/news/docview/421295668/fulltext/A928B4A3B2F14303PQ/3?accountid=10226\">\"Back To Basics; WHO KILLED HOMER? (book review)\"</a>. <a href=\"/wiki/Los_Angeles_Times\" title=\"Los Angeles Times\">Los Angeles Times</a><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">6 September</span> 2018</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=Back+To+Basics%3B+WHO+KILLED+HOMER%3F+%28book+review%29&amp;rft.date=1998-04-05&amp;rft.aulast=Knox&amp;rft.aufirst=Bernard&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fsearch.proquest.com%2Fnews%2Fdocview%2F421295668%2Ffulltext%2FA928B4A3B2F14303PQ%2F3%3Faccountid%3D10226&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AWho+Killed+Homer%3F\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-FukuyamaReview-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-FukuyamaReview_3-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Fukuyama, Francis. Foreign Affairs 77, no. 4 (1998): 121-22. doi:10.2307/20048981</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-KottaTradition-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-KottaTradition_4-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\">Kotta, Sandra (17 May 2017). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://quillette.com/2017/05/17/bald-men-fighting-comb-arguments-classical-tradition/\">\"Bald Men Fighting Over a Comb: Arguments About the Classical Tradition\"</a>. Quillette<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">6 September</span> 2018</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=Bald+Men+Fighting+Over+a+Comb%3A+Arguments+About+the+Classical+Tradition&amp;rft.date=2017-05-17&amp;rft.aulast=Kotta&amp;rft.aufirst=Sandra&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fquillette.com%2F2017%2F05%2F17%2Fbald-men-fighting-comb-arguments-classical-tradition%2F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AWho+Killed+Homer%3F\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-LewisUpdate-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-LewisUpdate_5-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\">Lewis, Paul (7 March 1988). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/1998/03/07/books/not-to-bury-homer-but-to-u